onal system. Contrary to the opinion of some authors, dong quai does not qualify as a phytoestrogen and does not appear to have any hormone-like actions in the body. This is partially supported by a double-blind trial with menopausal women that found no estrogenic activity for the herb. In Traditional Chinese Medicine, dong quai is rarely used alone and is typically used in combination with herbs such as peony and ligusticum for conditions such as menstrual cramps. Dong quai has been traditionally used as a way to promote formation of red blood cells, an effect partially supported in a case study of a man with kidney failure who had a significant improvement in anemia due to dialysis while drinking a tea composed of dong quai and peony.','Angelica Extract ','','publish','open','open','','angelica-extractdong-quai-ligustilide-1101-hplc','','','2013-09-16 05:25:53','2013-09-16 05:25:53','',0,'http://ansbotanics.com/?post_type=portfolio&#038;p=636',0,'portfolio','',0),(637,2,'2013-08-28 03:12:32','2013-08-28 03:12:32','','Angelica Extract(Dong Quai) Ligustilide','','inherit','open','open','','angelica-extractdong-quai-ligustilide','','','2013-08-28 03:12:32','2013-08-28 03:12:32','',636,'http://ansbotanics.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Angelica-ExtractDong-Quai-Ligustilide.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(638,2,'2013-08-28 03:13:56','2013-08-28 03:13:56','Product Name: Dong Quai(Angelica Sinensis) Extract (Ligusticum 1% HPLC)\r\n\r\nPlant Part Used: Root\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFunctions:\r\n\r\nDong Quai has long been referred to as \"female ginseng\" for many years in Traditional Chinese Medicne (TCM). In Traditional Chinese Medicine, dong quai is often included in herbal combinations for abnormal menstruation, suppressed menstrual flow, dysmenorrhea (painful menstruation), and uterine bleeding. It is not used in TCM for treating symptoms associated with menopause such as hot flashes. It is also used in TCM for both men and women with cardiovascular disease including high blood pressure and problems with peripheral circulation.\r\n\r\nTraditionally, dong quai is believed to have a balancing or \"adaptogenic\" effect on the female hormonal system. Contrary to the opinion of some authors, dong quai does not qualify as a phytoestrogen and does not appear to have any hormone-like actions in the body. This is partially supported by a double-blind trial with menopausal women that found no estrogenic activity for the herb. In Traditional Chinese Medicine, dong quai is rarely used alone and is typically used in combination with herbs such as peony and ligusticum for conditions such as menstrual cramps. Dong quai has been traditionally used as a way to promote formation of red blood cells, an effect partially supported in a case study of a man with kidney failure who had a significant improvement in anemia due to dialysis while drinking a tea composed of dong quai and peony.','Angelica Extract(Dong Quai) Ligustilide 1%/10:1 HPLC','','inherit','open','open','','636-revision-v1','','','2013-08-28 03:13:56','2013-08-28 03:13:56','',636,'http://ansbotanics.com/?p=638',0,'revision','',0),(639,2,'2013-08-28 03:42:49','2013-08-28 03:42:49','Product Name: Andrographis Powder Extract\r\n\r\nLatin Name: Andrographis Paniculata\r\n\r\nChinese Name: Chuan Xin Lian\r\n\r\nDescription:\r\n\r\nAndrographis paniculata is traditionally known as kalmegh. The plant belongs to family Acanthaceae and is widely used in Ayurvedic and Homeopathic medicine. The plant grows in waste grounds and prefers moist habitat. The flowers of the plant are insignificant and of dirty pink color. In Ayurveda the drug has been decribed a antipyretic ad hepatoprotective. Cold infusion of the drug is mentioned in Sushruta Samhita for fever an liver disorders. The plant has been used as a bitter tonic and a febrifuge. Recent research has thrown light on medicinal value of the plant.\r\n\r\nThere are four lactones in Andrographis paniculata: deoxyandrographolide, andrographolide, neoandrographolide and deoxydidehydroandrographolide. Andrographolide and total lactone are the common forms used in clinics. Animal studies on rat and mice conclude that all four lactones have anti-iflammatory through stimulating the adrenal gland and anti-pyretic effect. The most activ constituent and standardization is based on Andrographolide. The standardized extract contains 50%-95% of Andrographolide. he most significant pharmacological activities are anti-allergic, anti HIV, anti-inflammatory and anti-infection effects.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFunctions:\r\n\r\nHepatoprotective activity\r\n\r\nReduce cold symptoms\r\n\r\nHypoglycemicactivity\r\n\r\nAnti-fertility activity\r\n\r\nCardiovascular activity\r\n\r\nPsycho-pharmacological activity\r\n\r\nAnti-HIV activity\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Andrographis Paniculata  ','','publish','open','open','','andrographis-paniculata-andrographolide-5','','','2013-09-16 05:30:35','2013-09-16 05:30:35','',0,'http://ansbotanics.com/?post_type=portfolio&#038;p=639',4,'portfolio','',0),(640,2,'2013-08-28 03:39:32','2013-08-28 03:39:32','','Andrographis Paniculata Andrographolide 5%','','inherit','open','open','','andrographis-paniculata-andrographolide-5','','','2013-08-28 03:39:32','2013-08-28 03:39:32','',639,'http://ansbotanics.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Andrographis-Paniculata-Andrographolide-5%.doc',0,'attachment','application/msword',0),(641,2,'2013-08-28 03:40:29','2013-08-28 03:40:29','','Andrographis Paniculata Andrographolide','','inherit','open','open','','andrographis-paniculata-andrographolide','','','2013-08-28 03:40:29','2013-08-28 03:40:29','',639,'http://ansbotanics.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Andrographis-Paniculata-Andrographolide.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(642,2,'2013-08-28 03:42:49','2013-08-28 03:42:49','','Andrographis Paniculata Andrographolide 5%','','inherit','open','open','','639-revision-v1','','','2013-08-28 03:42:49','2013-08-28 03:42:49','',639,'http://ansbotanics.com/?p=642',0,'revision